03755nam a22005775i 9780226507675DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2017    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802265076757 a10.7208/97802265076752doi  a(DE-B1597)523699  a(OCoLC)1011673799  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aBL51b.L477 2018 7aREL0000002bisacsh04a2102231 aLevene, Nancy, eauthor.10aPowers of Distinction :bOn Religion and Modernity /cNancy Levene. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2017] 4cÂ©2017  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- t1. The Principle of Modernity -- t2. A History of Religion -- t3. Artificial Populations -- t4. The Collective -- t5. Images of Truth from Anselm to Badiou -- t6. The Radical Enlightenment of Spinoza and Kant -- t7. Modernity as Ground Zero -- t8. Of Gods, Laws, Rabbis, and Ends -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this major new work, philosopher of religion Nancy Levene examines the elemental character of religion and modernity. Deep in their operating systems, she argues, are dualisms of opposition and identity that cannot be reconciled with the forms of life they ostensibly support. These dualisms are dead ends, but they conceal a richer position-another kind of dualism constitutive of mutual relation. This dualism is difficult to distinguish and its concept of relation difficult to commit to. It risks contention and even violence. But it is also the indispensable support for modernity's most innovative ideals: democracy, criticism, and interpretation.   In readings from Abraham to the present, Levene recovers this richer dualism in its difference from the alternatives-other dualisms, nondualism, multiplication. From Abraham we get the biblical call to give up tribal belonging for a promised land of covenantal relation. Yet modernity, inclusive of this call, is also the principle that critiques the promise when it divides self from other, us from them. Drawing on a long tradition of thinkers and scholars even as she breaks new ground, Levene offers here nothing less than a new way of understanding modernity as an ethical claim about our world, a philosophy of the powers of distinction to include rather than to divide.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aModernism (Christian theology) 0aModernism (Christian theology). 0aReligionxPhilosophy. 4aAbraham. 4ademocracy. 4adistinction. 4adualism. 4amodernity. 4areligion. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226507675423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226507675.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles